Between 1970 and 2016, calving date significantly advanced by an estimated 0.15 (± 0.04 SE) days per year [95% CI = (-0.24, -0.07); 
  Fig 2a]. Across the 45-year study period, calving dates in female reindeer were estimated to have advanced by 6.8 days (
  Fig 2a). There was a tendency for the duration of the calving season to lengthen over time, i.e. a tendency for calving synchrony to weaken along the study period (
  b = 0.06 ± 0.07 SE; 
  Fig 2b) but this temporal trend was not statistically significant [95% CI = (-0.08, 0.21)].
